Falls City Public School Famlies,

Parents In Education (P.I.E.) is an organization that supports FCPS students. Each year, P.I.E. donates and supplies multiple things for the students within the district. P.I.E. funds all grade-level field trips and supplies for teachers and students through their multiple activities held throughout the year.

There are a few high school softball concession stand volunteer opportunities, including our tournament on September 12th. If you can volunteer an hour of your time to help working the concession stand, please complete the sign up: https://www.signupgenius.com/go/30e094ca8ae2fa7fc1-pie

The softball concessions stands are one of our biggest fundraisers for the year! Learn more about P.I.E. on their Facebook page.

Thanks for you continued support!

FCPS P.I.E. officers

post_text: Falls City Middle School has a new sports team in town! Falls City Public Schools joined the Nebraska Schools eSports Association (NSeSA) for the 20-21 school year. Thirty Tiger athletes will be competing in 6 man, 3 man, and single-player games of Overwatch, Rocket League, and StarCraft II. The fall season is 8 weeks long and FC will be competing weekly against Class C & D teams from around the state, with the first competition being next week against Silver Lake.

post_text:
Falls City FFA News:

With a crazy year we are glad to announce a crazy outcome! With the state convention this year being virtual the welding contest took on a new form. Participants welded at school and mailed in their welds to be evaluated. We would like to congratulate the following individuals. Our State welding team consisted of Thomas Fields, who placed 13th in ARC, Tyler Uhri, who placed 10th in TIG, Justin Brewer who placed 6th in MIG, and Raymond Feek, who placed 5th in OA, The Team placed very well with a 5th place finish! Congratulations!

Another achievement were the following who received state degrees, Keldon Campbell, Seth Brewer, Jack Findlay, and Gwen Olberding. For State Proficiencies we had 2 in the top 10 in the state in their respective area. Seth Brewer who placed top 10 in Grain Production placement, and Gwen Olberding who placed 2nd for Equine Science placement. Gwen received a plaque and would have walked on stage to receive it in person during convention. Thank you all for your hard work and dedication!

Falls City FFA Chapter Reporter

Kiley Nutt

post_text:
Falls City Middle School Parents,
This post is in regards to our pick up and drop off at middle school before and after school. We have been in consultation with the FCPD and the map below was designed in coordination with them. Please drop your students off in the parking lots either North or South of the building or in the parking lot on the east side of the building. Please do not pull over and drop students in the bus loading zone or on the east side of Morton Street.

FCPD will be issuing tickets to parents who drop students in the bus lane or that drop on the east side of Morton street in the no parking areas. It is also illegal to stop at the stop sign on 15th and Morton to let your kids out. Students should always cross using the marked cross walks.

Student safety is our first concern and this map provides us the best way of keeping our kids safe.

#FallsCityPoliceDepartment
text:
Falls City Middle School Parents,
This post is in regards to our pick up and drop off at middle school before and after school. We have been in consultation with the FCPD and the map below was designed in coordination with them. Please drop your students off in the parking lots either North or South of the building or in the parking lot on the east side of the building. Please do not pull over and drop students in the bus loading zone or on the east side of Morton Street.

FCPD will be issuing tickets to parents who drop students in the bus lane or that drop on the east side of Morton street in the no parking areas. It is also illegal to stop at the stop sign on 15th and Morton to let your kids out. Students should always cross using the marked cross walks.

Student safety is our first concern and this map provides us the best way of keeping our kids safe.

#FallsCityPoliceDepartment

post_text: FCMS 6th grade parents and new student parents. Tonight at 5:30 in the middle school gym we will be having our new student orientation. Attendance will be limited to 6th grade students and new students along with 2 adults per students. Please enter the South Entrance to the gym. You will be temperature checked upon entry and masks are encouraged. Please try to distance as much as possible once inside. We are excited to see you all tonight!

The staff and administration of Falls City High School have announced the selections for March Digital High School Students of the Month. The honors go to the following students:
Upperclassmen- Jack Findlay, a senior, is the son of Jeff and Susan Findlay. Alexis Wittwer, a junior, is the daughter of Gary and Andrea Wittwer.

Underclassmen- Joe Spinner, a freshman, is the son of Sherry Spinner. Piper Sutton, a sophomore, is the daughter of Shane and Alisha Sutton.

“The students were nominated by high school staff for being innovative, responsible, resilient, and resourceful in this digital learning environment,” according to high school principal Gale Dunkhas.

#digitallearning #keepingengaged #FCPublic

Sincere thanks to the person(s) that left this rock near FC Middle School that was found recently by Supt. Heckenlively. Additional "thank you" to all students and families for the special attention and support we received during Teacher Appreciation Week. Together... we are better!

The "Circle of Friendship (Black Cherry) Tree" was planted near central office/FCMS this week to represent the continually "growing" bond between students/peers at all ages across all FCPS buildings. BE KIND has been a common theme this year and we hope you will all help spread the seed of kindness within our community. Special thanks to Nemaha NRD.

post_text:
Each year the Falls City Education Foundation honors excellence in individuals through a series of awards. We honor those who have demonstrated excellence in teaching and contributions in promoting high-quality education in our school district. Please take the time to consider nominating individuals for these awards.

Awards presented include Outstanding Secondary Educator, Outstanding Elementary Educator, and Outstanding Classified Employee. The awards will be presented during the Pre-Service session on August 10th.

Nominations of individuals for these awards are now open. Packets including nomination forms, instructions, and rules are available for download on the homepage of the Falls City Public Schools website: www.fctigers.org. All nomination materials must be delivered or postmarked by June 26, 2020.

Recognizing outstanding individuals is one of the best ways to promote and highlight quality education and schools. I encourage you to nominate individuals who are deserving of recognition with these awards today!

Falls City Public Schools will be continuing to provide lunch through the summer break to students. This will be a lunch ONLY program starting on June 1st. Lunch will be provided Monday through Thursday with Fridays lunch included in the Thursday pickup. There WILL NOT be home deliveries made for the summer lunch program. All lunches will need to be picked up at the middle school each day between 11AM and 12:30PM. A lunch will be provided for all children between the ages of 1 and 18. If you would like to participate in our extended lunch program please click on the link below to fill out the application:

SENIOR ALERT The Richardson County Clerk’s Office has always made plans each election year to come to the High School and have a voter registration event for the Seniors. With the unfortunate circumstances this year we were unable to do that. We do want you to know that you still have time to REGISTER TO VOTE.

Any student, Senior or Junior who will be 18 on or before Tuesday, November 3, 2020 is eligible to register to vote now and vote in the Primary Election. You can click on this link:

https://co.richardson.ne.us/pdfs/election/2020/Voter%20Registration%20Form%20Fillable.pdf

and fill out your registration form, print and then sign and deliver to the drop box located on the north lower level entrance (18th Street) of the Richardson County Courthouse by 6:00 p.m. on Friday, May 1. If you have questions please call the Richardson County Clerk
at 402-245-2911.

post_text:
Congratulations to You-Ha Kim! Her entry into the Elks 2020 Americanism Essay Contest won the local and state contest in the 5th and 6th grade division. This year's essay theme was: "What Does Freedom of Speech Mean to Me?"

You-Ha will be receiving a check for $30.00 from the local Elk's Lodge of Falls City, and a $75.00 check from the state level, as well as certificates to recognize her accomplishment.
Her essay will be advanced to the Grand Lodge for national competition.

Congratulations are also given to Emmett Daake for 2nd place and to Chase Simpson for 3rd place in the local contest!

The staff and administration of Falls City High School have announced the selections for March Digital High School Students of the Month. The honors go to the following students:
Upperclassmen- Kade Bredemeier, a senior, is the son of Jason and Mandy Bredemeier. Maggie McNeely, a senior, is the daughter of Erik and Sandra McNeely.

Underclassmen- Cabe Marquez, a sophomore, is the son of Korey and Alysia Schawang and Randy Marquez. Abby Fritz, a sophomore, is the daughter of Darin and Kerry Fritz.

“The students were nominated by high school staff for being innovative, responsible, resilient, and resourceful in this digital learning environment,” according to high school principal Gale Dunkhas.

NOTICE - SPORTS PHYSICALS FOR 2020-21 DUE TO THE CORONAVIRUS:

Sports Physicals on file for the 2019-2020 school year for any current 9-11 grade students will now also be valid for the 2020-21 school year.

All incoming freshmen (current 8th graders) will still be required to provide sports physical paperwork that is dated no earlier than May 1, 2020.

The physicals that the current 7th-grade students have on file for the 2019-2020 school year can be used for NSAA/athletic purposes for the 2020-21 school year.

All incoming 7th-grade students (current 6th graders) will need to provide sports physical paperwork that is dated no earlier than May 1, 2020.

Physical forms will be available at Middle School after
May 1st.

High School students are asked to join their regular classes, via Zoom, starting Tuesday, April 14th. (Periods 3 & 4) The classes will run weekly Monday- Thursday from 10 am – 11:50 am. (schedule included as picture) These classes will meet once a week and reoccur on the same day of the week at the same time. We established this schedule to reduce conflicts and avoid crossover Zoom meetings. Zoom sessions will be recorded but we believe that the personal interaction and participation in these meetings will be engaging and beneficial for our students. You should be receiving email invitations from your teachers. We want to continue to connect, enrich, learn and give students opportunities to improve their grades.
#digitallearning #startsTuesday #FCPublic

Students, Parents, and Patrons,

Due to the extended closure of FCPS earlier this week through May 1st. Activities and scheduled events will continue to be postponed. Our first priority is to keep our students and families safe but to honor our students and traditions following recommendations from the Department of Education, Southeast Nebraska Department of Health, and NSAA. Information will continue to be updated as we are able to finalize plans. Major events impacted:

Prom- Postponed, options being explored to hold the event at a later date or different venue when safely allowed. Sponsors and groups will continue to collaborate.

Musical- Postponed, our sponsor will collaborate with students and parents.

District Music- Cancelled by NSAA

Alumni Volleyball/Basketball- Cancelled on the current date. Looking at future dates and options.

FFA Banquet/Officer Interviews- Postponed with options being explored by the adviser and student leadership.

If you have any questions reach out to us at the high school.
402-245-2116.

FCMS parents: Tonight after school your students will come home with a Manilla envelope. Inside you will find parent teacher conference portfolio materials. You will also find their 3rd quarter report card. In addition there will be other informational items that would have been given out in in P/T conferences. 6th and 7th grade students will also be signing up for lunch block classes today. The school will call parents to verify that their choices are acceptable to parents in the coming days.

Students will be bringing home all of their school items today. You will also be receiving information in the coming days on work that can be done at home over the break. Thank you for your patience as we work through the details and stay tuned for additional updates.

Effective Monday, March 16 all NSAA activity practices are suspended until Monday, March 30 and all NSAA activity competitions are suspended until Thursday, April 2. These suspensions may be extended should the conditions warrant.

Member schools and student-participants are expected to adhere to the NSAA Constitution & Bylaws and activity manuals during this time.

As more information becomes available, official updates will be posted on the NSAA website and the NSAA social media platforms.

post_text: Please be aware illness is among us in extraordinary numbers. The district does have several students out ill with influenza and strep. Please be knowledgeable of the symptoms and keep your child home if they are ill. Doctors usually recommend 5 days home if diagnosed with Influenza. If your child has been ill; please keep them home until they have a good day at home: no fever for 24 hours WITHOUT fever reducing medication, eating and drinking well, and not too tired to participate in ALL classes. We are encouraging the students to clean out lockers to have water bottles, bags, and winter garments (coats, hats, and gloves) washed. Our staff members are cleaning surfaces with disinfectant daily, encouraging good hand hygiene, and monitoring students for illness diligently.

post_text:
Falls City High School senior Braden Oliver signed his letter of intent on Wednesday, January 15, to play golf for the Hastings College Broncos. Oliver is a three-year varsity starter and letter winner. Oliver has earned several accolades in his three-year tenure. He was 2017 newcomer of the year, golfer of the year in 2019, and also qualified for the Nebraska Class B State meet as a junior. Oliver medaled in every meet in 2019 and was crowned champion at HTRS Invite and Raider Golf Invite. Braden is a three-sport athlete and has received multiple awards in his other sports. Bradon is the son of Brad and Kim Oliver. Coach Marsh, Hastings College coach, is excited to sign Braden and looks forward to the contributions he will make on the team.
Pictured L to R: Lee Kurpgeweit, Craig Marsh, Braden Oliver, and Joe Dunn.
#nextlevel #broncogolf #tigerproud #FCPublic

post_text:
On Monday November 18th, 24 juniors from Falls City High School were able to attend County Government Day at the Richardson County Courthouse. Included in the day's activities was a tour of the county offices, and jobs of Richardson County. A Jeopardy style contest between the participating schools in which Falls City High defeated Humboldt-TRS 490-420. After the contest, students were able to listen to Senator Julie Slama speak on state and local issues. Students also enjoyed lunch at the local Elk's #963 chapter, and finished the day with a tour of the Richardson County Jail. Mr. Josh McCampbell, Social Science Instructor, sponsored the students for this local learning opportunity.
#handsonlearning #thankyourichardsoncounty #FCPublic

post_text:
Michelle Beer has signed a letter of intent to play volleyball for Bethany College, Kansas. Michelle has been a standout middle blocker on the Falls City volleyball team. She has been a four year starter along with being a four year letter winner for the Lady Tigers. In her four years on the court, Michelle has totaled 569 career kills with 284 coming in her senior year. Throughout her career Michelle also developed her passing game and added 417 digs in her career with over half of them coming in her senior year. Michelle contributed 97 career total blocks and 87 career aces. Her knowledge of the game of volleyball and her natural drive to play at a high level has allowed her to develop into a great six rotation volleyball player. Michelle was also a team captain this past season for the Tigers. Michelle is the duaghter of Mike and Deena Beer. Pictured with Michelle are her parents Mike and Deena, current coach Ali Heimes, former coach Julie Frederick, and Bethany Volleyball Coach Brandi Stewart.
#movingon #tigerproud #FCPublic

post_text: Falls City Middle School is happy to announce that a chapter of National Junior Honor Society will commence this Spring. National Junior Honor Society (NJHS) is an organization established to recognize outstanding middle-level students who have demonstrated excellence in the areas of Scholarship, Leadership, Service, Character, and Citizenship. Students in grades 6-8 who are full-time students with a 3.5 GPA for the first semester (among other criteria) receive an invitation to fill out a Candidate Information Form to be considered for membership. The goal of NJHS is to build leaders and all-around great young adults, along with promoting community involvement. NJHS members select activities and officers along with his/her own individual service project every semester that best reflects his/her personal interests.

post_text:
On October 22nd the Falls City FFA joined with B103.1 to help serve the farmers an appreciation lunch at Consolidated Grain and Barge. From the hours of 11-1 Jack Findlay, Braydon Frederick, Laney Feek, Gracie Frederick and Gwen Olberding stuffed sack lunches. While Seth Brewer, Tyler Uhri, Justin Brewer, and Ray Feek delivered it to them at the scales. Gwen Olberding was also interviewed by B103.1 about what FFA means to her and why it is an important program in our schools. Our chapter has been helping with Feed the Farmers for 3 years and we plan to continue in the future.

Chapter Reporter ~ Gracie Frederick

Photo #1- Seth Brewer and Tyler Uhri deliver lunch to a farmer at the scales.

Photo #2- Jack Findlay checks bags to make sure the farmers get a full meal.

Photo #3- Gwen Olberding gives each farmer various merchandise donated by sponsors.

Photo #4- Laney Feek and Braydon Frederick wrap hot dogs for each lunch.
#supportingourfarmers #ffa #FCPublic

Falls City Middle School Parents you will be receiving a letter in the mail in the next couple of days addressing various items.

One of the items included is an instructional guide to access our Safe Schools website and app. With this program parents and students can submit tips to the administration with concerns. These tips can be anonymous or they can have your name attached. The user has a choice. When would you use such a program? If your students says something to you that you think the school should know about OR if you witness something that you think the school should know about it would be appropriate for you to use this app. This is just another tool to enhance communication between home and school. Check your mail over the next few days for more information on how to get connected to the Safe Schools app.

post_text: FCMS hosted its 12th annual Chautauqua night on Tuesday evening. What is Chautauqua? It is a chance for 8th grade students to pick a theme and then dress up as characters related to the theme and provide an oral history to parents and visitors who pass through the hallways. In order for the students to perform for the visitors the visitors must pay them a fee. All the proceeds from the evening are then donated to charity. This years 8th grade classes collected $765 dollars for charity. Not only do students have the opportunity to do research and practice their public speaking skills, they also get to do some good for the community. Special thanks go out to Mr. Huppert and Mr. Munford for organizing the event. Just another reason why it is great to be a Tiger!

post_text:
Falls City Middle School parents you will be receiving a letter in the next few days with information about a few various items.

The first item deals with our pick up and drop off at middle school before and after school. We have been in consultation with the FCPD and the map below was designed in coordination with them. For some parents this will not change how you drop off and pick up your students. However, for those of you that drop off or pick up on Morton street in front of the school or in the bus lane you need to be familiar with this map. FCPD will begin issuing tickets to parents who drop students in the bus lane or that drop on the east side of Morton street in the no parking areas. It is also illegal to stop at the stop sign on 15th and Morton to let your kids out. Students should always cross using the marked cross walks.

Student safety is our first concern and this map provides us the best way of keeping our kids safe. Falls City Police Department

Falls City Art students designs selected for Community Medical Center Centennial celebration.

Mazey McCullough’s design was used for staff polo shirts.

post_text: Congratulations to the Falls City Middle School September AOK award winners: Morgan Dumont 7th grade, Ryker McCullough 6th grade and Wyatt Olberding 8th Grade. Acts of Kindness are nominated by staff and students throughout the month. At the end of the month staff collect the AOK nominations and then remove the names from each act. These students were nominated by other students and adults in our building for demonstrating acts of kindness that went above and beyond. They displayed the type of Falls City pride and citizenship that make us all proud. Congratulations Charlie, Rae and Gabe for making our school a great place to learn and grow! It's always a great day to be a Tiger!

post_text: Greetings Falls City Middle School parents. Thursday September 19th at 7PM in the middle school cafeteria we will have our first parent and principal night. This is an unstructured time where Mr. Bangert can share what has been going on in the middle school with parents. It is also a time when parents can share concerns or ask questions of the principal. The purpose is to encourage dialogue between the home and school to ensure the best educational outcomes for our community. We hope to see you on Thursday night!

Mrs. Weinert has been at the high school 10 years and in the district 31. Ellicyn Gilkerson, 2019 graduate, won a national goal medal for art work that was submitted.
Her work was in the top 1% of 340,000 submitted.
